{"title": "FLARE: Faithful Logic-Aided Reasoning and Exploration", "domain": "LLM_NLP", "seeds": [{"problem": "Chain-of-Thought (CoT) prompting often yields unfaithful intermediate reasoning and struggles with multi-step planning; neuro-symbolic approaches that offload to external solvers require strictly executable code and falter on ambiguous, fuzzy reasoning tasks.", "method": "FLARE prompts an LLM to (i) draft a natural-language plan, (ii) formalize the query as a Prolog-style logic program of facts/relations/goals, and (iii) simulate code execution as a multi-hop search trace with backtracking—without using external solvers and without requiring code executability. The LLM performs Prolog-like DFS subgoal decomposition and traversal via few-shot examples of code and traces, enabling soft reasoning over loosely formalized concepts while maintaining interpretable structure."}, {"problem": "There is no built-in, principled way to assess whether an LLM’s intermediate reasoning faithfully reflects the computation it claims to perform.", "method": "FLARE measures faithfulness by executing the subset of generated Prolog programs that are syntactically correct to obtain exact solver traces and comparing them to the LLM’s simulated search from the same code using ROUGE-Lsum over line-wise steps. This yields a quantitative faithfulness score, and experiments show a strong positive correlation between this score and task accuracy across models and datasets."}, {"problem": "LLM reasoning lacks tools to diagnose hallucinated steps and inefficient exploration, making it hard to understand why reasoning fails.", "method": "FLARE extracts facts and relations from both the generated code and the simulated search to detect inconsistencies: hallucinations when the search uses items absent from the code, and sub-optimality when code items go unused. It also tracks unique emergent facts and relation overlap. Empirically, correct traces exhibit an 18.16% higher share of unique emergent facts, 8.60% higher code–search relation overlap, and a 3.62% lower rate of unused relations than incorrect traces, providing actionable diagnostics of reasoning quality."}]}
